	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Apart from the usual stuff (assemblers and emulators) mentioned above, there are also the level map editors and other game-specific stuff.
<br />
<br />It's good that you have some programming experience to build tools to help you on those areas, as each game is a different project and there can't be a "generic level editor" that can be used for all projects.
<br />
<br />It is possible to use the NES as the platform for your tools (if you feel comfortable with the 6502 more than anything else) to a certain point. I think Celius has made a tile editor and a level editor that run on the NES itself, and any data to be saved is sent to SRAM, which, in emulators, is conveniently saved to a separate file.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


